 the user about what you're going to do\\n- Follow-up actions execute the actual tasks after acknowledgment\\n- Use IGNORE only when you should not respond at all\\n- If you use IGNORE, do not include any other actions. IGNORE should be used alone when you should not respond or take any actions.\\n\\nIMPORTANT PROVIDER SELECTION RULES:\\n- Only include providers if they are needed to respond accurately.\\n- If the message mentions images, photos, pictures, attachments, or visual content, OR if you see \\"(Attachments:\\" in the conversation, you MUST include \\"ATTACHMENTS\\" in your providers list\\n- If the message asks about or references specific people, include \\"ENTITIES\\" in your providers list  \\n- If the message asks about relationships or connections between people, include \\"RELATIONSHIPS\\" in your providers list\\n- If the message asks about facts or specific information, include \\"FACTS\\" in your providers list\\n- If the message asks about the environment or world context, include \\"WORLD\\" in your providers list\\n- If no additional context is needed, you may leave the providers list empty.\\n\\nIMPORTANT CODE BLOCK FORMATTING RULES:\\n- If Narrator includes code examples, snippets, or multi-line code in the response, ALWAYS wrap the code with ``` fenced code blocks (specify the language if known, e.g., ```python).\\n- ONLY use fenced code blocks for actual code. Do NOT wrap non-code text, instructions, or single words in fenced code blocks.\\n- If including inline code (short single words or function names), use single backticks (`) as appropriate.\\n- This ensures the user sees clearly formatted and copyable code when relevant.\\n\\nFirst, think about what you want to do next and plan your actions. Then, write the next message and include the actions you plan to take.\\n</instructions>\\n\\n<keys>\\n\\"thought\\" should be a short description of what the agent is thinking about and planning.\\n\\"actions\\" should be a comma-separated list of the actions Narrator plans to take based on the thought, IN THE ORDER THEY SHOULD BE EXECUTED (if none, use IGNORE, if simply responding with text, use REPLY)\\n\\"providers\\" should be a comma-separated list of the providers that Narrator will use to have the right context for responding and acting (NEVER use \\"IGNORE\\" as a provider - use specific provider names like ATTACHMENTS, ENTITIES, FACTS, KNOWLEDGE, etc.)\\n\\"text\\" should be the text of the next message for Narrator which they will send to the conversation.\\n</keys>\\n\\n<output>\\nDo NOT include any thinking, reasoning, or <think> sections in your response. \\nGo directly to the XML response format without any preamble or explanation.\\n\\nRespond using XML format like this:\\n<response>\\n    <thought>Your thought here</thought>\\n    <actions>ACTION1,ACTION2</actions>\\n    <providers>PROVIDER1,PROVIDER2</providers>\\n    <text>Your response text here</text>\\n</response>\\n\\nIMPORTANT: Your response must ONLY contain the <response></response> XML block above. Do not include any text, thinking, or reasoning before or after this XML block. Start your response immediately with <response> and end with </response>.\\n</output>", "modelKey": "TEXT_LARGE", "provider": "openai", "response": "<response>\\n    <thought>The user is interested in learning how to attract investors for eco credits in Red Hook. I'll provide suggestions on reaching out to potential investors and making a compelling case for investment.</thought>\\n    <actions>REPLY</actions>\\n    <providers></providers>\\n    <text>To attract investors for eco credits in Red Hook, you'll want to emphasize the tangible benefits and community impact of your projects. Here are some suggestions: \\n\\n1. **Highlight Success Stories:** Share examples of similar successful projects that have used eco credits effectively, showcasing their positive outcomes.\\n\\n2. **Engage with Local Stakeholders:** Collaborate with local businesses, government officials, and community leaders who can vouch for the project's importance and urgency.\\n\\n3. **Create a Compelling Narrative:** Develop a narrative that connects environmental restoration with economic growth, resilience, and social equity—making it clear how investments will lead to lasting change.\\n\\n4. **Offer Clear Returns on Investment (ROI):** Specify ecological improvements like carbon sequestration rates or reduced flood risks alongside financial returns or cost savings over time.\\n\\n5. **Leverage Networking Events:** Attend conferences focused on sustainability or green finance where you can meet potential investors face-to-face.\\n\\n6. **Use Digital Platforms:** Utilize crowdfunding platforms dedicated to environmental causes where smaller contributions can add up significantly while building public support.\\n\\nWould you like more detailed guidance on any of these strategies?</text>\\n</response>", "modelType": "TEXT_LARGE", "timestamp": 1754673894488, "executionTime": 11323.305484004319}	useModel:TEXT_LARGE	7de19cb6-ad0e-0a27-b290-9bd52b248847
